Fetch all tweets on Patient Experience¶

Syntax for multiple keyword search: use OR AND NOT logical operators. Space between words is implicitly converted to AND In our example, we need to keep track of the search term used, so I chose to fetch them individually instead of using logical operator query

Let's get all the latest tweets for Patient Experience¶

##There are many tweets with no text and outside of US location and they all get classified as Neutral, so avoid collecting such data
locationFilter = ['queensland australia', 'india', 'canada', 'london', 'london england', 'malaysia']
def searchTwitter(keyword, results, count):
    keyword = keyword + ' patient'
    i = 0
    for tweet in tweepy.Cursor(api.search, q=keyword+'-filter:retweets',
                                   tweet_mode='extended', locale = 'en').items(count):
            #ignore tweets in other languages for the purpose of this exercise
            i+=1
            text = trimToNone(tweet.full_text)
            #print(tweet.user.location, "\n\n\n")    
            if text == 'None' or text is '' or text is None:
                pass
            elif tweet.lang != 'en':
                pass
            elif tweet.place is not None and (tweet.user.location).strip().lower() in locationFilter:
                pass
            
            results.append(tweet)
            #print(tweet, "\n\n\n")    
                
    print('Total tweets for term: ', keyword, ' ', i)   

def trimToNone(text):
    if text is None:
        return 'None'
    if len(text.strip()) == 0:
        return 'None'
    return text

Create a dataframe from the tweets¶

In [4]:
#function to extract data from and convert tweet object to data frame
columns = ['id', 'full_text', 'retweet_count', 'created_at', 'user.id', 
           'user.screen_name', 'user.name', 'user.derscription', 'user.followers_count', 'user.friends_count',
          'user.location']
def tweetToDataFrame(tweets):
    DataSet = pd.DataFrame()
    DataSet['tweetID'] = [tweet.id for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['tweetText'] = [tweet.full_text for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['tweetRetweetCt'] = [tweet.retweet_count for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['tweetFavoriteCt'] = [tweet.favorite_count for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['tweetSource'] = [tweet.source for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['tweetCreated'] = [tweet.created_at for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userID'] = [tweet.user.id for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userScreenName'] = [tweet.user.screen_name for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userName'] = [tweet.user.name for tweet in tweets]
    #DataSet['userCreateDt'] = tweet['user']['created_at]
    DataSet['userDesc'] = [tweet.user.description for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userFollowerCt'] = [tweet.user.followers_count for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userFriendsCt'] = [tweet.user.friends_count for tweet in tweets]
    DataSet['userLocation'] = [tweet.user.location for tweet in tweets]
    return DataSet

import re
def removeURL(text):
    try:
        text = re.sub(r"http\S+", " ", text)
    except Exception:
        pass
    #print(text)
    return text

Let's first clean the URL from tweet text before running cleanText to make sure we strip all the space etc correctly I'm removing URLs so that it doesn't mess up the bag of words with junk short link texts in later steps which I found to be the case while working on this exercise

tweet_frame['tweetText'] = tweet_frame['tweetText'].apply(removeURL) tweet_frame['userDesc'] = tweet_frame['userDesc'].apply(removeURL)

##clean up utf-8 characters, remove white space, we will leave emojis as they are
import html
def cleanText(text):
    try:
        if hasattr(text, '__iter__'):
            text = html.unescape(text)
        text = text.strip(' \t\n\r')
        text = text.replace('"','')
        #different type of double quote 
        text = text.replace('', '')
        text = text.replace('#','')
        text = text.replace('.','')
        text = text.replace(',','')
        if type(text) is str:
            text = text.lower()
    except UnicodeDecodeError:
        text = 'Unicorn encounter'    
    except Exception:
        pass
    #print(text)
    return text

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def extractHTMLTagText(text):
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text)
    text = soup.text
    #print(text)
    return text

tweet_frame = tweet_frame.applymap(cleanText) tweet_frame.head()

#Function to generate word clouds from text

from PIL import Image
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS, ImageColorGenerator
import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def show_words_cloud(text, stopwords, count):
    location = os.path.realpath(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'twitter_logo_mask.png'))
    image = Image.open(location)
    twitter_mask = np.array(image)
    wcloud = WordCloud(collocations=False, background_color='white',max_words=count,
                       mask=twitter_mask, max_font_size=90,
                       stopwords=stopwords, width=1267, 
                       height=1024, random_state=997)

    wcloud.generate(text)
    image_colors = ImageColorGenerator(twitter_mask)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
    plt.imshow(wcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout(pad=0)
    plt.show()

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer


boldStart = "\033[1m"
boldEnd = "\033[0;0m"

def featureCounts(vectorizer, cv_dm=None, *features):
    for feature in features:
        if cv_dm is None:
            cv_dm = vectorizer.fit_transform(feature)
        print(boldStart + "\nFeature space: " + feature.name + boldEnd ,cv_dm.shape)
        names = vectorizer.get_feature_names()   #create list of feature names
        count = np.sum(cv_dm.toarray(), axis = 0) # add up feature counts 
        count2 = count.tolist()  # convert numpy array to list
        count_df = pd.DataFrame(count2, index = names, columns = ['count']) # create a dataframe from the list
    return count_df.sort_values(['count'], ascending = False)[0:10]  #arrange by count instead of alphabetical (top 20)

# NLTK also has tokenizers 
import nltk
from nltk import word_tokenize

def tokenize(row):
    text = cleanText(row.lower())
    wordList = str(text.lower()).split() #splits the text apart before stemming
    token2Text = ''
    wordPos = pos_tag(wordList)
    for item in wordPos:
        if item[0] not in stopwords:
            token2Text = token2Text + ' ' + item[0]
        token2Text = token2Text.replace('jobs', 'job')
    if trimToNone(token2Text) == 'None':
        print(text)
    #print(token2Text)    
    return token2Text


def pos_tag(word):
    token2Text = nltk.pos_tag(word)
    return token2Text

import nltk

def pos_tag(row):
    tokenText = word_tokenize(cleanText(row))
    token2Text = nltk.pos_tag(tokenText)
    #print(token2Text)
    #if empty array
    if not token2Text:
        return ''

    return token2Text

patientexpDf['pos'] = patientexpDf["tokenText"].apply(lambda x: pos_tag(x))

#Simple topic engine with PoS tagging
def topic(inputstring):
    #print(inputstring)
    #bucket counts and sign
    techLeglCount = 0
    wlbCount = 0
    imprvCount = 0
    
    i=0
    for word in inputstring:
        prev = inputstring[i-1]
        #print(word)
        ##Now increase count of every bucket the current word belongs to
        if word[0] in GIWlb:
            wlbCount+=1
            #print(word[0] + "wb")
        if word[0] in GIstatement:
            techLeglCount+=1
            #print(word[0] + "tech")
        if word[0] in GIArea:
            imprvCount+=1
            #print(word[0] + "improv")
        i+=1
    
    #print("Tech =", techLeglCount)
    #print("Well being =", wlbCount)
    #print("Area improve =", imprvCount)
    
    label = ''
    if techLeglCount > 2:
        label = label +  'Tech '
    if wlbCount > 2:
        label = label +  'WellBeing '
    if imprvCount > 2:
        label = label +  'AreaOfImprovement '

    if label == '':
        label = max3(techLeglCount, 'Tech ', wlbCount, 'WellBeing ', imprvCount, 'AreaOfImprovement ')
    #print(sentiment,"\n****************\n")
    return label

def max3(x, xlab,y, ylab, z, zlab):
    Max = x
    Maxlbl = xlab
    if y > Max:
        Max = y
        Maxlbl = ylab
    if z > Max:
        Max =z
        Maxlbl = zlab
    #print(Max)
    return Maxlbl

#Simple topic engine with PoS tagging
def sentiment(inputstring, penalize=False):
    #print(inputstring)
    #bucket counts and sign
    
    sentimentCount = 0
    i=0
    for pos in inputstring:
        word = pos[0]
        #print("word=", word)
        ##Now increase count of every bucket the current word belongs to
        if word in GIpos or word in GIstrong:
            sentimentCount+=1
        elif word in GIneg or word in GIweak:
            sentimentCount-=1
        i+=1
    
    #print("Tech =", techLeglCount)
    #print("Well being =", wlbCount)
    #print("Area improve =", imprvCount)
    
    label = 'Neutral'
    if sentimentCount > 0:
        label = 'Positive'
    elif sentimentCount < 0:
        label = 'Negative'

    #print(sentiment,"\n****************\n")
    return label

The sentiment and topic assigned to tweets is definitely likely to change with a different sentiment dictionary. Even within GI, modifications to our sentiment calculation like adding weights for degree of sentiment would change our analysis. GI has over 12000 words and we added several custom words. For our current data our sentiment calculation is very good and as we collect more data it would definitely be something we will revisit and adapt to the trends
